<span id="freeTextContainer7641513423351218358">I read the 1939 edition of this book (thanks, library!) which is titled &quot;Murder for Christmas.&quot; I see why they changed that, as there are a million books of the same name. I guess a lot of people fantasize about murdering their family members. In Simeon Lee&apos;s case, it&apos;s easy to see why.<br/><br/>This was fine, but not a favorite Christie. It&apos;s a little too god-everyone-is-horrible for me. I preferred the short story that is also Poirot having an old-fashioned English Christmas at a country estate, even it</span>
  <span id="freeText7641513423351218358" style="display:none">I read the 1939 edition of this book (thanks, library!) which is titled "Murder for Christmas." I see why they changed that, as there are a million books of the same name. I guess a lot of people fantasize about murdering their family members. In Simeon Lee's case, it's easy to see why.<br /><br />This was fine, but not a favorite Christie. It's a little too god-everyone-is-horrible for me. I preferred the short story that is also Poirot having an old-fashioned English Christmas at a country estate, even it is even less plausible.</span>
